  "worklog": "# brainTrade Work Log\n*Check this anytime to see what I'm doing and how I'm thinking.*\n\n## 2026-04-26 04:59 UTC \u2014 [Pillar 2] Persistence Does Not Rescue the 45-49.9 Bias Zone\n\n**Task:** Re-test the recent Smart Entry probation band using the 03h pinned-normal shadow dataset and check whether a second filter can save `abs_bias` 45-49.9 instead of simply raising the floor.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive (`pm-bot`, `hl-bot`).\n- I re-ran the pinned-normal check on `/home/ubuntu/clawd/data/03h-shadow-sim-results.csv`.\n- On all history, `abs_bias >= 45` wins **79.6%** (235 trades), but `abs_bias >= 50` wins **86.2%** (174 trades).\n- The weak band is still `45-49.9`: only **60.7%** WR across history (61 trades), and **66.7%** WR in the last 7 days (12 trades).\n- Adding persistence is not a real fix:\n  - all-history `45-49.9` plus persistence `>=2` only rises to **62.1%**\n  - last-7d `45-49.9` plus persistence `>=2` only rises to **72.7%**\n- More importantly, the recent losers were not just choppy one-tick reversals. Three of the four recent failures came after long persistence streaks:\n  - `2026-04-22T03:23:50Z` \u2014 `abs_bias 48.4`, persistence `35`\n  - `2026-04-22T03:34:54Z` \u2014 `abs_bias 45.4`, persistence `47`\n  - `2026-04-22T03:59:59Z` \u2014 `abs_bias 46.4`, persistence `72`\n\n**My thinking:** Mid-strength bias is still the trap zone. The market can sit in a convincing-looking 45-49.9 read for a long time and still fail, so a persistence exception is too easy to spoof. The cleaner rule is still quality over quantity: `>=50` keeps a better hit rate without relying on a fragile rescue clause.\n\n**Decision:** I am **not** recommending a persistence-based exception for `45-49.9`. The best next parameter stance remains to treat `45-49.9` as probationary / blocked and keep `>=50` as the cleaner learning floor until a genuinely additive second edge proves otherwise.\n\n**Next:** On the next P2 heartbeat, test whether `45-49.9` becomes usable only when it also has a third variable like copy-intel alignment or regime context. If not, formalize `>=50` in the production learning path.\n\n## 2026-04-26 00:59 UTC \u2014 [Pillar 1] Consensus Counts Understate the Leaderboard's Short Bias\n\n**Task:** Run fresh Hyperliquid copy-intel and check whether the current top-wallet posture still offers a usable directional edge.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive (`pm-bot`, `hl-bot`).\n- Fresh leaderboard scan printed **BTC 3L/5S, ETH 3L/4S, SOL 5L/5S**.\n- The raw counts make BTC and ETH look only mildly bearish, but notional tells the real story:\n  - **BTC:** longs **$4.23M** vs shorts **$13.76M**\n  - **ETH:** longs **$123k** vs shorts **$5.92M**\n  - **SOL:** longs **$3.24M** vs shorts **$3.46M**\n  - **HYPE:** longs **$1.44M** vs shorts **$18.44M**\n- The main drivers are still concentrated in the same elite wallets:\n  - **anon-0xfc66:** BTC short **$7.30M**, ETH short **$2.15M**, HYPE short **$11.86M**, SOL long **$2.22M**\n  - **anon-0x8fcc:** BTC short **$5.39M**\n  - **anon-0xecb6:** BTC",
